Distinguish between upper and lower motor neuron injury symptoms
SLO 1

Upper: mild muscle wasting, spasticity and hypertonia
Lower: significant muscle wasting, hypotonia
Why are there more cervical nerves/roots than vertebrae?

A patient presents with left leg weakness. Leg extension is 2/5 strength and patellar reflex is 4+. Which of the following is the most likely location of injury?
A. Ipsilateral upper motor neuron, L1
B. Contralateral upper motor neuron, S1
C. Ipsilateral lower motor neuron, L4
D. Contralateral lower motor neuron, S1
E. Quadriceps muscle fibers

A-→hyper reflexia indicate an upper motor neuron injury. Hyper reflexia at the level of the patella indicates a dermatome of around L1.
We don't know for sure if the injury is contralateral, but it must have been ipsilateral at some point because upper motor neurons start ipsilaterally, then descend and dessicate

Mr. Thompson, a 82yM admitted to your hospital for an expanding intracranial tumor that is non-resectable and has not responded to chemo and radiation. The family has decided to pursue hospice care. Over the last few days his mental status deteriorated and he is now unresponsive. During your neurological exam, his response to pain is posturing seen below.

1. How can the difference between the two help you identify the level of injury?

1. Decorticate occurs if the lateral and medial brainstem pathways are both intact.
 Decerebrate if the lateral pathway (from the red nucleus) is disrupted, but medial pathways remain intact. I.e. the origin of the injury is distal to the red nucleus, but above the medial pathway.
Any kind of posturing=normal motor cortex/corticospinal pathway is disrupted
What would a right sided lesion at T10 result in in the spinothalamic tract?

Traveling up 1-2 levels clinical results in the following: sometimes a lesion of the right-sided T10 level results in ipsilateral loss of pain/temperature experienced from T10 through T12 and than contralateral loss of pain/temperature below T12.

One more time!
-Spinothalamic tract functions={{c1::pain, temp, and touch}}. Part of the {{c2::ascending}} pathway. Can cause {{c3::contralateral and ipsilateral}} symptoms. Decussation {{c4::in cord near level it is sensing}}. 
-Lateral corticospinal tract functions={{c5::voluntary motor control (upper and lower motor neurons).}} Decussation in {{c6::medullary pyramids}}. Can cause i{{c7::psilateral and contralateral symptoms.}} Part of the {{c8::descending}} pathway
-Posterior/dorsal columns functions={{c9::proprioception, touch, position and vibration.}} {{c10::Ipsilateral}} symptoms only. Motor and sensory neurons. Part of the {{c11::ascending}} pathway. Decussation={{c12::none}}
